  "summary_short": "A historical fiction novel set against the backdrop of the 1984-85 UK miners' strike, exploring themes of solidarity, activism, and social change through the eyes of a young activist in London.",
  "summary_long": "<p>In the back rooms of Britain’s 1980s, where coal dust clung to coats and music carried further than any speech, a small circle begins recording what the country is trying to forget. Cassettes labelled in thick marker, VHS tapes passed hand to hand, names written down and crossed out again. Strikes, gigs, coach meetings, late night phones, a walkie talkie crackling with callsigns that sound like jokes until they don’t.</p><br><p>The Enemy Within follows the people living inside that pressure, ordinary, stubborn, frightened, funny, and furious, as protest turns into organisation, organisation turns into risk, and every decision starts to feel like it will echo for decades. It is a story about loyalty and betrayal, about who gets to tell the nation’s story, and what happens when the truth is archived by those who have the least power to protect it.</p><br><p>Somewhere in all that noise is a single recording that could change everything, if it survives long enough to be heard.</p>",
